{
  "texts": [
    "A key advantage of HSI is its non-invasive nature, which enables the examination of food materials without causing any damage or change (Kamruzzaman et al. 2015; Sim et al. 2024).",
    "Additionally, HSI is also valuable in environmental monitoring, such as detecting changes in vegetation, assessing forest health, or monitoring land-use alterations (Lee et al. 2024).",
    "It has practical applications in food industries for quality control, like identifying defects or contaminants in food products (Ordoudi et al. 2014; Wu et al. 2023; Sunil et al. 2023).",
    "Overall, these benefits demonstrate the versatility of HSI, making it a valuable tool for a range of potential applications in the agriculture and food sectors (Mahesh et al. 2015; Lu et al. 2020; Khan et al. 2022; Wang et al. 2023; Esmaeily et al. 2024).",
    "Despite its vast potential, the adoption of HSI technology faces several challenges (Li et al. 2017; He et al. 2022; Khan et al. 2022; Zhang et al. 2022)."
  ]
}